{"title_page": "Miya people", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = '''Miya People'''<br /><small>'''\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be'''</small>\n| image = \n| caption = \n| population = {{Circa |7&nbsp; million| Ik=yes}}\n| popplace = {{flag|India}} ([[Assam]]) 6.4 million (20.04%)\n| langs = Mix of [[Bengali language]] plus [[Assamese language]] with Urdu and Persian loan words.\n| rels = [[Islam]]\n| related = [[Bengali Muslim]] , [[Sylhetis]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Miyas''' ({{lang-as|\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be}}) or '''Bhatiya''' a colloquial term commonly used for Bengali origin Muslims in the Northeast Indian State of [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/08/assams-miya-proving-you-are-indian/|title=Assam\u2019s \u2018Miya\u2019: Proving You Are Indian|author=Priyanka Borpujari|website=The Diplomat|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref> The Miyas are [[Bengali Muslim]] [[ethnoreligious group]] that originated in the [[British Indian]] province of Bengal, which later became [[East Bengal]] during the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)]].<ref name=\"indilens.com\">{{cite web|url=https://indilens.com/514954-miya-muslim-and-assamese-socio-cultural-history-of-assam/|title=Miya, Muslim and Assamese Socio-Political History of Assam|date=7 September 2016|website=Indilens.com|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/alifa-assamese-cinema-miya-muslims-illegal-immigrants-bangladeshi-urban-poverty-/story/1/23324.html|title=Why all 'Miya Muslims' are seen as Bangladeshis in Assam|website=Dailyo.in|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nMiyas have a population of almost 6.4 million which is spread throughout Assam covering 20% of the state Population, though they are mainly concentrated in [[Barpeta district|Barpeta]], [[Dhubri district|Dhuburi]], [[Goalpara district|Goalpara]], [[Kamrup district|Kamrup]], [[Nagaon district|Nagaon]], [[Darrang district|Darrang]], [[Chirang district|Chirang]], [[Kokrajhar district|Kokrajhar]], [[South Salmara district|South Salmara]], [[Nalbari district|Nalbari]], [[Morigaon district|Morigaon]], and [[Bongaigaon district|Bongaigaon]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://asu.thehoot.org/media-watch/media-practice/dehumanising-muslims-in-assam-9661|title=Dehumanising Muslims in Assam|date=23 December 2016|website=thehoot.org|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Term==\nMiya is a term used for Muslims who can trace their roots to East Bengal, but in places like Barpeta, Chirang, and Bongaigaon the term Shayk is used to describe them.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} In Dhuburi, Kokrajhar, Goalpara, and South Salmara, they refer to themselves as Bhatiya, and in Nagaon, Darrang, Morigaon, and Hojai they use the term Miya for themselves.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Sometimes they are also known as Mymensinghia.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Assamese poet [[Jyotiprasad Agarwala]] termed them as Na-Asamiya because they adopted [[Assamese people|Assamese]] culture and language.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Many scholars use the term Bongomuliya musalman (East Bengal rooted Muslims) and also Bengali Muslims. Finally, A group educationists and intellectuals have decided to accept their ethnicity as Miya in Assam.<ref name=\"indilens.com\"/>\n\n==Language==\nThe language of the Miya people consists of various [[Bengali-Assamese languages]] spoken in current [[Bangladesh]] and [[Assam]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Many of those languages are treated as Bengali dialects although many of them have significant difference from Bengali (as much as Assamese and Odia has).{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} A popular definition of the term only includes Mymensinghiya speaking Muslims and their descendants and Mymensinghiya language. While the East Bengal origin people who speak other languages like Sylheti, Nokhailla, etc. call themselves and their languages as Sylheti, Nokhailla, etc.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} respectively. The Miya officially adopted the Assamese language during the language movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indilens.com/518937-east-bengal-rooted-muslim-or-miyah-and-line-system-in-assam-1920/|title=East Bengal rooted Muslim or Miyah and Line System in Assam-1920|date=11 December 2016|website=Indilens.com|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>{{clarify|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Miya Poetry==\nMany scholars from Miya community are trying to uplift the Miya society through poems. They have chosen Poverty, Child marriage, Population bomb, Illiteracy as their subject . The collection of these poems are termed as [[Miya Poetry]]. But in recent time due to context of some poems, it creates a controversy in Assam, especially among indigenous people of Assam.[https://timesofindia. Indiatimes.com]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/hafiz-ahmed-assam-miyah-poetry|title=Interview {{!}} There is a Conspiracy to Show Bengal-Origin Muslims as Anti-Assamese: Hafiz Ahmed|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> [<ref>https://bengali.indianexpress.com/opinion/assam-miya-poetry-history-politics-identity-135975/ \u0986\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09b0 \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8, \u09ad\u09c2\u0997\u09cb\u09b2 \u0993 \u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09ae</ref>]\n\n==Identity Crisis==\nMiya people or Muslims of Bengal origin suffer identity crisis. They are often termed as Miya in a derogatory sense by other communities. They are identified as Miyas, Bengali Muslim, East Bengal rooted Muslims, Na-Asamiya, Pamua Musalman, Charua Musalman, Shaikh and Bhatiya also. That's why scholars are trying to end this identity crisis and make Miya an identity.A student once asked Bruce Lee \"You teach me fighting, but you talk about peace. How do you do both together?\".\nBruce Lee replied \"Spread peace. But whenever you see a Bangladeshi Miya, beat the sh*t out of him.\"<ref>https://www.bbc.com/bengali/news-48994118 \u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 '\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be' \u09a8\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0986\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09b0\u09cd\u0995 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8?</ref>]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Assam]]\n[[Category:Bengal]]\n[[Category:People of Bangladeshi descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = '''Miya People'''<br /><small>'''\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be'''</small>\n| image = \n| caption = \n| population = {{Circa |7&nbsp; million| Ik=yes}}\n| popplace = {{flag|India}} ([[Assam]]) 6.4 million (20.04%)\n| langs = Mix of [[Bengali language]] plus [[Assamese language]] with Urdu and Persian loan words.\n| rels = [[Islam]]\n| related = [[Bengali Muslim]] , [[Sylhetis]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\n'''Miyas''' ({{lang-as|\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be}}) or '''Bhatiya''' a colloquial term commonly used for Bengali origin Muslims in the Northeast Indian State of [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/08/assams-miya-proving-you-are-indian/|title=Assam\u2019s \u2018Miya\u2019: Proving You Are Indian|author=Priyanka Borpujari|website=The Diplomat|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref> The Miyas are [[Bengali Muslim]] [[ethnoreligious group]] that originated in the [[British Indian]] province of Bengal, which later became [[East Bengal]] during the [[Partition of Bengal (1905)]].<ref name=\"indilens.com\">{{cite web|url=https://indilens.com/514954-miya-muslim-and-assamese-socio-cultural-history-of-assam/|title=Miya, Muslim and Assamese Socio-Political History of Assam|date=7 September 2016|website=Indilens.com|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyo.in/arts/alifa-assamese-cinema-miya-muslims-illegal-immigrants-bangladeshi-urban-poverty-/story/1/23324.html|title=Why all 'Miya Muslims' are seen as Bangladeshis in Assam|website=Dailyo.in|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nMiyas have a population of almost 6.4 million which is spread throughout Assam covering 20% of the state Population, though they are mainly concentrated in [[Barpeta district|Barpeta]], [[Dhubri district|Dhuburi]], [[Goalpara district|Goalpara]], [[Kamrup district|Kamrup]], [[Nagaon district|Nagaon]], [[Darrang district|Darrang]], [[Chirang district|Chirang]], [[Kokrajhar district|Kokrajhar]], [[South Salmara district|South Salmara]], [[Nalbari district|Nalbari]], [[Morigaon district|Morigaon]], and [[Bongaigaon district|Bongaigaon]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://asu.thehoot.org/media-watch/media-practice/dehumanising-muslims-in-assam-9661|title=Dehumanising Muslims in Assam|date=23 December 2016|website=thehoot.org|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Term==\nMiya is a term used for Muslims who can trace their roots to East Bengal, but in places like Barpeta, Chirang, and Bongaigaon the term Shayk is used to describe them.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} In Dhuburi, Kokrajhar, Goalpara, and South Salmara, they refer to themselves as Bhatiya, and in Nagaon, Darrang, Morigaon, and Hojai they use the term Miya for themselves.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Sometimes they are also known as Mymensinghia.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Assamese poet [[Jyotiprasad Agarwala]] termed them as Na-Asamiya because they adopted [[Assamese people|Assamese]] culture and language.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Many scholars use the term Bongomuliya musalman (East Bengal rooted Muslims) and also Bengali Muslims. Finally, A group educationists and intellectuals have decided to accept their ethnicity as Miya in Assam.<ref name=\"indilens.com\"/>\n\n==Language==\nThe language of the Miya people consists of various [[Bengali-Assamese languages]] spoken in current [[Bangladesh]] and [[Assam]].{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Many of those languages are treated as Bengali dialects although many of them have significant difference from Bengali (as much as Assamese and Odia has).{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} A popular definition of the term only includes Mymensinghiya speaking Muslims and their descendants and Mymensinghiya language. While the East Bengal origin people who speak other languages like Sylheti, Nokhailla, etc. call themselves and their languages as Sylheti, Nokhailla, etc.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} respectively. The Miya officially adopted the Assamese language during the language movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indilens.com/518937-east-bengal-rooted-muslim-or-miyah-and-line-system-in-assam-1920/|title=East Bengal rooted Muslim or Miyah and Line System in Assam-1920|date=11 December 2016|website=Indilens.com|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref>{{clarify|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Miya Poetry==\nMany scholars from Miya community are trying to uplift the Miya society through poems. They have chosen Poverty, Child marriage, Population bomb, Illiteracy as their subject . The collection of these poems are termed as [[Miya Poetry]]. But in recent time due to context of some poems, it creates a controversy in Assam, especially among indigenous people of Assam.[https://timesofindia. Indiatimes.com]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/hafiz-ahmed-assam-miyah-poetry|title=Interview {{!}} There is a Conspiracy to Show Bengal-Origin Muslims as Anti-Assamese: Hafiz Ahmed|website=The Wire|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> [<ref>https://bengali.indianexpress.com/opinion/assam-miya-poetry-history-politics-identity-135975/ \u0986\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09b0 \u0987\u09a4\u09bf\u09b9\u09be\u09b8, \u09ad\u09c2\u0997\u09cb\u09b2 \u0993 \u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09ae</ref>]\n\n==Identity Crisis==\nMiya people or Muslims of Bengal origin suffer identity crisis. They are often termed as Miya in a derogatory sense by other communities. They are identified as Miyas, Bengali Muslim, East Bengal rooted Muslims, Na-Asamiya, Pamua Musalman, Charua Musalman, Shaikh and Bhatiya also. That's why scholars are trying to end this identity crisis and make Miya an identity.[<ref>https://www.bbc.com/bengali/news-48994118 \u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 '\u09ae\u09bf\u099e\u09be \u0995\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09be' \u09a8\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0986\u09b8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09b0\u09cd\u0995 \u0995\u09c7\u09a8?</ref>]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Assam]]\n[[Category:Bengal]]\n[[Category:People of Bangladeshi descent]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4065:e1d:60a2::b1c9:3901", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIdentity Crisis)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miya_people"}
{"title_page": "Mal\u00e9ku language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Guatuso\n|nativename=Mal\u00e9ku Ja\u00edka\n|states=[[Costa Rica]]\n|ethnicity = 1,070 [[Maleku people]] (200?)<ref name=e18/>\n|speakers=750\n|date=2000\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Chibchan languages|Chibchan]]\n|fam2=[[Votic languages|Votic]]\n|iso3=gut\n|glotto=male1297\n|glottorefname=Mal\u00e9ku Ja\u00edka\n}}\n==Classification==\nThe '''Malku Ja\u00edka language''', also called malecu, maleku, '''Guatuso''', '''Watuso-W\u00e9tar''', and '''Guetar'''  is a member of the Voltic branch of the Chibchan language family. \nMal\u00e9ku, or \u2018the speech of our people\u2019, is considered to be endangered according to '''The Endangered Languages Project'''. According to the 2011 National Population Census, 67.5% of the population that lives in the Maleku official territory declared that they speak the language; however, the state of vitality varies from one village to another and even among families (S\u00e1nchez 2011). In any case, following the parameters of UNESCO, the language can be classified as definitively endangered (S\u00e1nchez 2013).\n\n==History==\nThe malekus (usually called \"Guatusos\" in historical documents, travel chronicles of the 19th and 20th centuries, and in multiple academic studies) constitute one of the original peoples of the Costa Rican territory. While their contact with the Hispanic language and culture was extremely sporadic and limited at least until the second mid-nineteenth century (Constenla, 1988; Castillo,2004), it can be assumed that this contact was intensified in the middle of the twentieth century. \n\n==Geographic distribution==\n\n'''Official status'''\nThe Maleku is an indigenous language of north-central [[Costa Rica]], in the area of Guatuso, in the province of Alajuela, Costa Rica. It is spoken by around 300 to 460 indigenous [[Mal\u00e9ku people]] in an area of 2994 hectares. The aboriginal group that speaks Mal\u00e9ku is also known as the ''Guatusos''. They live in three communities called Palenques in the northern area of Costa Rica: Margarita, Tonjibe and El Sol. According to Constenla (1998), the Guatuso is in a state of decline in Margarita (the largest village) and in a state of resistance in Tonjibe and El Sol. At the 2000 census, 71.1% of the members of the ethnic group declared themselves to speak the language, but only 49% considered it as the mother tongue.  The 2011 National Census of Population reported that 67.5% of the population in these communities speaks this language (Avenda\u00f1o 2018). The Ministry of Education (MEP, Minienciclopedia de los Territorios Ind\u00edgenas de Costa Rica 2017) reported a Mal\u00e9ku population of 498 inhabitants. According to this institution, children attending schools in the region of Guatuso receive bilingual instruction in Mal\u00e9ku and Spanish.  According to Espinoza Romero, Mej\u00eda Mar\u00edn & Ovares Barquero 2011, the school, traditionally an acculturation mechanism, has not contributed to strengthening the Mal\u00e9Ku identity. For instance, students receive instruction of core subjects in Spanish. They have to learn how to read and write in Spanish first. When they already read and write in the mainstream language, they can learn their language. The authors claim that the norm has been the teaching of the official language: Spanish and that despite the existence of educational policies that contemplate the revitalization of the use of indigenous languages in the region, there is an absence of strategies for teaching aboriginal languages.  \n\n'''Dialects/Varieties'''\n\nThe speakers of these three communities have declared that there are differences between the variety spoken by the communities of Margarita and El Sol and the one that is spoken by the people of Tonjibe (Avenda\u00f1o 2018). [[Corobic\u00ed language|Corobic\u00ed]] is possibly a dialect. \n\n=Phonology=\n\n'''Vowels''' \n\nMaleku has five vowels. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Vowels\n! colspan=\"2\" |front\n! colspan=\"2\" |central\n! colspan=\"2\" |back\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"2\" |unrounded\n! colspan=\"2\" |unrounded\n! colspan=\"2\" |rounded\n|-\n!\n!long\n!\n!long\n!\n!long\n|-\n|high\n|i\n|i\u02d0\n|\n|\n|u\n|u\u02d0\n|-\n|higher mid\n|e\n|e\u02d0\n|\n|\n|o\n|o\u02d0\n|-\n|low\n|\n|\n|a\n|a\u02d0\n|\n|\n|}\nSource: http://www.lapsyd.ddl.cnrs.fr/lapsyd/index.php?data=view&code=758\n\n'''Vowel notes:'''\n\nS\u00e1nchez (1984) affirms that the vowel system of the Maleku is similar to Spanish (apart from length contrast); he cites some words with unlike VV sequences but is unclear if these are single nuclei or V.V. \n\nSmith Sharp (1979) argues for V.V with an optional desyllabification of high vowels to approximants [w, j], in agreement with Costenla Uma\u00f1a (1983).\n\n'''Stress'''\n\nS\u00e1nchez (1984) argues that stress is contrastive.  The examples given suggest there may be role for morphological structure and vowel length in predicting stress placement. Smith Sharp (1979: 42) states \"En maleku, hay una sola oposici\u00f3n de acento. Cada palabra tiene por los menos un acento primario que no es predecible en palabras de dos o m\u00e1s s\u00edlabas.\"\n\n'''Consonants''' \n\nThe traditional consonant system of the Maleku includes fifteen phonemes:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"5\" |Consonants \n! rowspan=\"2\" |bilabial\n! rowspan=\"2\" |dental\n! rowspan=\"2\" |alv\n! rowspan=\"2\" |pal-al\n! rowspan=\"2\" |velar\n|-\n!Airstream\n!Manners\n!ERA features\n!Secondary source\n!Voicing properties\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" |pulm\n|stop\n|\n|\n| -vless\n|p\n|t\u032a\n|\n|\n|k\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |aff\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n| rowspan=\"2\" |sib\n| -vless\n|\n|\n|\n|\u1e6f\u0283\n|\n|-\n| -ved\n|\n|\n|\n|\u1e0f\u0292\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |fric\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n<br />\n\n|\n| -vless\n|\u0278\n|\n|\n|\n|x\n|-\n|sib\n| -vless\n|\n|\n|s\n|\n|\n|-\n|lat\n|\n| -vless\n|\n|\n|\u026c\n|\n|\n|-\n|nasal\n|\n|\n| -ved\n|\n|\n|n\n|\n|\n|-\n|trill\n|\n|\n| -ved\n|m\n|\n|r\n|\n|\u014b\n|-\n|tap/flat\n|\n<br />\n|\n|'''-ved'''\n|\n|\n|\u027e\n|\n|\n|-\n|appr\n|lat\n|\n|'''-ved'''\n|\n|\n|l\n|\n|\n|}\n\nSource: http://www.lapsyd.ddl.cnrs.fr/lapsyd/index.php?data=view&code=758\n\n\nConsonant notes:\n\nS\u00e1nchez (1984) reports /t/ as 'dental-alveolar' and other coronals as 'alveolar'.  Contrast between /\u026c, x/ appears to be in process of being lost in favor of /x/ (Costenla Uma\u00f1a 1983). Influence from Spanish has added voiced stops and /\u0272/ to the modern colloquial language; these are not included in the inventories of S\u00e1nchez (1984), Smith Sharp (1983) or in the text counts of Krohn (2017). Costenla Uma\u00f1a (1983) excludes them from his 'heritage inventory'.\n\nSyllabic notes:\n\n(C)V(\u02d0)(C) seems to be the basic pattern, with no clusters, as suggested by Smith Sharp (1983: 44).  Any C can occur in onset (except rhotics word-initially); any C except affricates, fricatives and /\u027e/ in coda.  S\u00e1nchez (1984) gives 2 examples of word-internal CC codas /r\u0278, rp/ in /irp-t\u0283ia, ir\u0278-la\u014b/ \"drink it, eat it\" and suggests CVCC as max syllable, but such examples are described as the result of an optional loss of a vowel in the 2nd person ergative prefix /ri\u0278a/ by Costenla Uma\u00f1a (1983: 18)\n\nCanonical Form:\n(C)V(\u02d0)(C)\n\t\nSyllabic Restriction:\n(C)V(\u02d0)(C)\n\n== Grammar ==\n\n=== Word order ===\nThe basic order of the elements is variable in transitive and in intransitive clauses. In intransitive clauses the common order is SV, but it is also possible to find VS order.\n\nFor example:  T\u00f3   na- t\u00f3ye\n\nYo  1E    ir  \n\nI      go \n\n=== Subjects and objects ===\nMaleku possesses an ergative\u2013absolutive actancial system. \n\n==== Subject of an intransitive verb ====\nIn intransitive clauses the subject is expressed in absolutive case. The affixes that  appear in the verb establish a concordance of the person with the subject. These are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+intransitive clauses \n!1 person \n!2 person\n!3 person\n|-\n|na\n| -mi, -ma\n| -i, -a\n|}\n\n==== Subject of a transitive verb ====\nIn transitive clauses Maleku distinguishes between complete  and incomplete  transitive clauses. The affixes that  appear in the verb are common in both constructions. These are \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+transitive clauses \n!1 person \n!2 person\n!3 person\n|-\n| -rra\n| -rrifa\n-rrif\n\n-rrf\n\n-rrip\n\n-rrfa\n\n-rrp\n<br />\n| -rri\n|}\n\n==== Number ====\nMaleku distinguishes between singular and plural in common nouns. The plural is expressed in two ways.\n{|\n!\n!Example                          \n!Translation\n|-\n|'''duplicate noun'''\n| colspan=\"2\" |toc\u00f3            \u2192car\u00fa                 ear\ntoc\u00f3toc\u00f3     \u2192 car\u00facar\u00fa         ears\n\n\n\n<br />\n|-\n|'''plural modifier \"mar\u00e1ma\"'''\n| colspan=\"2\" |yuqu\u00ed                        \u2192     bowie knife           \nyuqu\u00ed   mar\u00e1ma        \u2192     bowie knives      \n\nnalhac\u00e1                    \u2192      brother\n\nnalhac\u00e1    mar\u00e1ma  \u2192       brothers\n<br />\n|}\n<br />\n\n=== Personal pronouns ===\nThere are four personal pronouns in Maleku. These are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!1\u00b0 person singular\n!2\u00b0 person singular\n!1\u00b0 person plural (exclusive)\n!1\u00b0 person plural (inclusive)\n|-\n|T\u00f3n~ t\u00f3\u2192 I    \n|p\u00f3~ p\u00fao\u2192 you \n|To\u00ed~ to\u00ed\u2192 we\n|T\u00f3tiqu\u00ed~ totiqu\u00ed\u2192 we\n|}\n<br />\n== Written System ==\nThe alphabet of Maleku was proposed by the linguist Adolfo Constenla, and it was adopted as official by the ''Asesor\u00eda de Educaci\u00f3n Ind\u00edgena del Ministerio de Educaci\u00f3n Publica de Costa Rica''. \n \n'''Vowels''' \n{|\n!'''phoneme'''\n!grapheme\n|-\n|\u0430\n|a\n|-\n|e\n|e\n|-\n|i\n|''i''\n|-\n|o\n|''o''\n|-\n|u\n|''u''\n|}\n\n\n\n'''Consonants''' \n{|\n!'''phoneme'''\n!grapheme\n|-\n|p\n|''p''\n|-\n|t\n|''t''\n|-\n|k\n|''c,qu''\n|-\n|t\u0283\n|''ch''\n|-\n|d\u0292\n|y\n|-\n|\u0278\n|f\n|-\n|s\n|s\n|-\n|x\n|j\n|-\n|\u026c\n|lh\n|-\n|l\n|l\n|-\n|\u027e\n|r\n|-\n|r\n|rr\n|-\n|m\n|m\n|-\n|n\n|n\n|-\n|\u014b\n|nh\n|}\n\n\n==Vocabulary ==\n*kapi kapi = hello (with a knocking gesture on your partner's shoulder)\n*afekapian = Thank you\n*w-ay = yes\n*hebet = no\n*fufu = morfo butterfly\n*niskak = bird\n*pili = toucan\n*pek-pen = frog\n*gnou-ek = red-eye frog\n*ti-fakara = waterfall\n*irri miotem? = what is your name?\n*mioten ... = my name is ...\n*arrachapi kahole = I would like a cup of coffee\n*errekeki kerakou = let's go (to a place)\n*erreke malehila =let's go swimming\n\n===Numbers<ref name=\"Native Languages of the Americas\">[http://www.native-languages.org/maleku_words.htm Native Languages of the Americas]</ref>===\n*Dooka = One\n*P\u00e1ngi = Two\n*Po\u00f3se = Three\n*Pak\u00e1i= Four\n*Ot\u00edni= Five\n\n===Common Nouns<ref name=\"Native Languages of the Americas\" />===\n*Och\u00e1pak\u00e1= Man\n*Kur\u00edjur\u00ed= Woman\n*Toji= Sun\n*Tlijii= Moon\n*Lak\u00e1= Earth\n*Oktara= Stone\n*Koora= Tree\n*Uu= House\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Barrantes, R., Smouse, P. E., Mohrenweiser, H. W., Gershowitz, H., Azofeifa, J., Arias, T. D., & Neel, J. V. (1990). Microevolution in lower Central America: genetic characterization of the Chibcha-speaking groups of Costa Rica and Panama, and a consensus taxonomy based on genetic and linguistic affinity. American Journal of Human Genetics, 46(1), 63\u201384.\n*Brinton, Daniel G. 1891. The American Race: A Linguistic Classification and Ethnographic Description of the Native Tribes of North and South America. New York: N. D. C. Hodges Publisher\n*Guatuso. Retrieved from http://multitree.org/codes/gut.html\n*Madrigal Cordero, P., & Sol\u00eds Rivera, V. (2012). Recognition and Support of ICCAs in Costa Rica. Kothari et al.\n*Ma