rs and links// Emergency contact numbers]\n|-\n! Most services are available 24h and seven days a week\n|}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Czech Republic|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Czech Republic|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Algernon (psychiatrick\u00fd experiment)", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Czech_Republic"}
{"title_page": "Aleksandra Mir", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Aleksandra Mir\n| image          = \n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth year|1967}}\n| birth_place    = Lubin, Poland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| education     = University of Gothenburg, School of Visual Arts, New School for Social Research\n| field         = \n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = [[Baloise Art Prize]] (2004)\n| spouse        = \n| partner          =\n| website          = {{URL|aleksandramir.info/}}\n}}\n\n'''Aleksandra Mir''' (born 1967) is a Swedish-American<ref name=\"Sculpture Unlimited Symposium interview\">{{cite web |author1=Harald Starzer |author2=Christian Ohlinger |title=Interview with Aleksandra Mir |url=https://www.aleksandramir.info/bibliography/starzer_harald_ohlinger_christian_interview-with-aleksandra-mir_sculpture-unlimited-sympos |website=Sculpture Unlimited Symposium |accessdate=24 April 2020 |location=Institute of Fine Arts, Kunstuniversitat Linz}}</ref> [[contemporary art]]ist known for her collaborative installations and projects.\n\n==Life and work==\nMir was born in Lubin, Poland in 1967<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=0714878774 |page=276}}</ref> She grew up in Sweden, lived in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Palermo]], [[Sicily]],<ref name=sandra/> Mir studied at the [[University of Gothenburg]], the [[School of Visual Arts]] and the [[The New School|New School for Social Research]].<ref name=\"Guggenheim\">{{cite web |title=Aleksandra Mir |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/aleksandra-mir |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> She lives in London.<ref name=tate/> \n\nHer work has been shown at [[Tate Modern]], London; at the [[Schirn Kunsthalle]], [[Frankfurt]]; <ref name=sandra>Sandra Danicke, [http://www.fr-online.de/kunst/frankfurter-schirn-plunder-des-triumphs,1473354,2820148.html/ Plunder des Triumphs], ''Frankfurter Rundschau'', 13 May 2009</ref> at [[M - Museum Leuven]]<ref name=\"De Standaard\">{{cite web |last1=Steverlynck |first1=Sam |title=Een kleine stap voor een vrouw |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20131204_00871485 |website=De Standaard |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=nl-BE}}</ref>; at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York City<ref name=\"artnet News\">{{cite web |last1=Cascone |first1=Sarah |title=10 Must-See Whitney Contemporary Works |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/contemporary-artworks-new-whitney-291295 |website=artnet News |accessdate=1 January 2020 |date=24 April 2015}}</ref>;<ref name=\"Interview Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Donnelly |first1=Ryann |title=Built to Spill |url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/built-to-spill |website=Interview Magazine |accessdate=1 January 2020 |date=25 September 2011}}</ref> and at the Mercosul Biennial in [[Porto Alegre]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Ga\u00fachaZH\">{{cite web |title=Obra que simula queda de sat\u00e9lite em Porto Alegre abre 9\u00aa Bienal do Mercosul |url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/noticia/2013/09/obra-que-simula-queda-de-satelite-em-porto-alegre-abre-9-bienal-do-mercosul-4266335.html |website=Ga\u00fachaZH |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=pt-BR |date=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n''The How Not to Cookbook'', (Collective Gallery, Edinburgh, 2009 and [[Rizzoli New York|Rizzoli]], NYC 2010) collected advice from 1,000 home cooks from around the world who explained what ''not'' to do in the kitchen.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/food/realfood/article1787039.ece/ Alex Renton], ''Never boil and avocado, and other handy tips'', The Times, 20 August 2009</ref><ref name=\"Eat Me Daily\">{{cite web |last1=Forbes |first1=Paula |title=The How Not to Cookbook: Lessons Learned the Hard Way, the Anti-Cookbook \u2013 Eat Me Daily |url=http://www.eatmedaily.com/2009/08/the-how-not-to-cookbook-lessons-learned-the-hard-way-the-anti-cookbook/ |website=Eat Me Daily |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>, ''The How Not to Cookbook: Lessons learned the Hard Way, the Anti-Cookbook'', Eat Me Daily, 24 August 2009\n\nIn ''First Woman on the Moon'' (1999), Mir converted a Dutch beach into a moonscape for one day with the help of bulldozers.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir1/ Lars Bang Larsen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203141602/http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir1/ |date=2008-12-03 }}, ''First Woman on the Moon'',  Frieze, London, #50, January 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/life_and_times/ Will Bradley] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110909012739/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/life_and_times/ |date=2011-09-09 }}, ''Life and Times: Aleksandra Mir'', Frieze, Issue 75, 2003</ref><ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all_the_world/ Nancy Spector] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722165740/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all_the_world/ |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''All the World...'', Frieze, Issue 98, London, April, 2006</ref> The video of this event has been presented at multiple venues,<ref>[http://www.volkskrant.nl/beeldende-kunst/kunstenares-mir-landt-op-strand~a518934/ Jeroen Junte], ''Kunstenares Mir landt op strand'', De Volkskrant, Amsterdam, 27 August 1999</ref><ref>[https://artforum.com/inprint/issue=200302&id=4185// Tim Griffin], ''Openings: Aleksandra Mir'', Artforum, NYC, February 2003</ref> at the [[International Space University]], Strasbourg  <ref>[http://www.isunet.edu/about/master-of-space-studies/faculty-and-lecturers/213 Lecturers], International Space University, Strasbourg, 2015</ref> and at the UK Space Conference, Liverpool, 2015.<ref>[http://ukspace2015.co.uk/speakers Speakers], UK Space Conference, Liverpool, 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Mir painted the [[Mandela Way T-34 Tank]] pink with [[Cubitt Artists]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Gibbs | first=Jonathan | title=Talk of the Town: Pink Tank | date=2 November 2003 | publisher=The Independent on Sunday | url=http://www.aleksandramir.info/texts/gibbs.html | access-date=2017-01-01 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050904183740/http://www.aleksandramir.info/texts/gibbs.html | archive-date=2005-09-04 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFor ''Newsroom 1986\u20132000'' (2007), Mir with a group of assistants copied 240 NYC tabloid covers in felt-tip marker and mounted them in an ever-revolving installation to simulate the daily workings of a Manhattan newsroom.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir2/ Steven Stern] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828115935/http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir2/ |date=2010-08-28 }}, ''Newsroom'', Frieze, #115, London, May 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/yesterdays-front-page-turns-into-todays-art/article1327587/ Simon Houpt], ''Yesterday's front page turns into today's art'', The Globe and Mail, Toronto, October 22, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/20/arts/design/20head.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=aleksandra%20mir&st=cse Roberta Smith], ''New York Stories: Art Torn Screaming From the Headlines, Then Hung on Walls'', New York Times, October 20, 2007</ref><ref>[http://arthistorian.wordpress.com/page/2/ gninja], ''Review of \"Newsroom 1986 \u2013 2000\": What Is Roberta Smith Going on About?'', Art(h)ist'ry, 20 October 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.brooklynrail.org/2007/11/artseen/mir Jen Schwarting], ''Aleksandra Mir Newsroom 1986-2000'', The Brooklyn Rail, NYC, November, 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/09/911-art-empire-150910054837804.html James Reinl], ''9/11 art and the 'Course of Empire' '', Al Jazeera, NYC, 10 September 2015</ref> Mir has created a series of large scale murals using only [[Sharpie (marker)|Sharpie]] marker pens.<ref>[http://diepresse.com/home/kultur/kunst/4736377/Albertina_Zeichnungen-zimmern  Johanna Hofleitner], ''Albertina: Zeichnungen zimmern'', Die Presse, Vienna, 21 May 2015</ref>\n\nIn ''Triumph'' she collected 2529 trophies from the general public of Sicily and exhibited them all in one installation at the Schirn Kunsthalle, Frankfurt (2009). It traveled to the [[South London Gallery]] for the [[London Olympics]] in 2012.<ref>[http://www.itsnicethat.com/articles/aleksandra-mir Catherine Gaffney], ''Going for Gold: Aleksandra Mir investigates our relationship with the trophy'', itsnicethat, London, July, 2012</ref>\n\nMir has created ''Plane Landing'', a real size helium inflatable jet plane, meant not to fly, but to hover above the ground as \"a sculpture of a jet plane in a permanent state of landing\".<ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/a-sligo-group-show-dreams-big-and-succeeds-visual-art-round-up-1.2332129 Aidan Dunne], ''A Sligo group show dreams big and succeeds'', The Irish Times, Dublin, 10 September 2015</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs]\n\n<ref name=tate>Stuart Comer, Valentina Ravaglia ([s.d.]). [http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/display/aleksandra-mir Aleksandra Mir]. Tate Modern. Accessed March 2016.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sculpture-unlimited.info/archive/en/aleksandra_mir_en.html Sculpture Unlimited, Institute for the Fine Arts and Cultural Studies, Linz, Austria]\n* [http://oceans.taraexpeditions.org/en/m/art/artists/aleksandra-mir/ Tara Expeditions, Antarctica]\n* [https://drawingroom.org.uk/resources/aleksandra-mir/ Aleksandra Mir at Drawing Room, London]\n* [http://whitney.org/Exhibitions/AmericaIsHardToSee?&artwork_id=7923&filter_id=36/ Aleksandra Mir at Whitney Museum of American Art, New York]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160306014246/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/artwork/15529/ Aleksandra Mir at Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, New York]\n* [http://www.southlondongallery.org/page/pursuit-of-perfection/ Aleksandra Mir at South London Gallery]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mir, Aleksandra}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The New School alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish women artists]]\n[[Category:B\u00e2loise Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Swedish contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Swedish women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name           = Aleksandra Mir\n| image          = \n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth year|1967}}\n| birth_place    = Lubin, Poland\n| death_date     = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| education     = University of Gothenburg, School of Visual Arts, New School for Social Research\n| field         = \n| training      =\n| movement      = \n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        = [[Baloise Art Prize]] (2004)\n| spouse        = \n| partner          =\n| website          = {{URL|aleksandramir.info/}}\n}}\n\n'''Aleksandra Mir''' (born 1967) is a Swedish-American<ref name=\"Sculpture Unlimited Symposium interview\">{{cite web |author1=Harald Starzer |author2=Christian Ohlinger |title=Interview with Aleksandra Mir |url=https://www.aleksandramir.info/bibliography/starzer_harald_ohlinger_christian_interview-with-aleksandra-mir_sculpture-unlimited-sympos |website=Sculpture Unlimited Symposium |accessdate=24 April 2020 |location=Institute of Fine Arts, Kunstuniversitat Linz}}</ref> [[contemporary art]]ist known for her collaborative installations and projects.\n\n==Life and work==\nMir was born in Lubin, Poland in 1967<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=0714878774 |page=276}}</ref> She grew up in Sweden, lived in [[New York City|New York]] and [[Palermo]], [[Sicily]],<ref name=sandra/> Mir studied at the [[University of Gothenburg]], the [[School of Visual Arts]] and the [[The New School|New School for Social Research]].<ref name=\"Guggenheim\">{{cite web |title=Aleksandra Mir |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/aleksandra-mir |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> She lives in London.<ref name=tate/> \n\nHer work has been shown at [[Tate Modern]], London; at the [[Schirn Kunsthalle]], [[Frankfurt]]; <ref name=sandra>Sandra Danicke, [http://www.fr-online.de/kunst/frankfurter-schirn-plunder-des-triumphs,1473354,2820148.html/ Plunder des Triumphs], ''Frankfurter Rundschau'', 13 May 2009</ref> at [[M - Museum Leuven]]<ref name=\"De Standaard\">{{cite web |last1=Steverlynck |first1=Sam |title=Een kleine stap voor een vrouw |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20131204_00871485 |website=De Standaard |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=nl-BE}}</ref>; at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York City<ref name=\"artnet News\">{{cite web |last1=Cascone |first1=Sarah |title=10 Must-See Whitney Contemporary Works |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/contemporary-artworks-new-whitney-291295 |website=artnet News |accessdate=1 January 2020 |date=24 April 2015}}</ref>;<ref name=\"Interview Magazine\">{{cite web |last1=Donnelly |first1=Ryann |title=Built to Spill |url=https://www.interviewmagazine.com/art/built-to-spill |website=Interview Magazine |accessdate=1 January 2020 |date=25 September 2011}}</ref> and at the Mercosul Biennial in [[Porto Alegre]], Brazil.<ref name=\"Ga\u00fachaZH\">{{cite web |title=Obra que simula queda de sat\u00e9lite em Porto Alegre abre 9\u00aa Bienal do Mercosul |url=https://gauchazh.clicrbs.com.br/cultura-e-lazer/noticia/2013/09/obra-que-simula-queda-de-satelite-em-porto-alegre-abre-9-bienal-do-mercosul-4266335.html |website=Ga\u00fachaZH |accessdate=1 January 2020 |language=pt-BR |date=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n''The How Not to Cookbook'', (Collective Gallery, Edinburgh, 2009 and [[Rizzoli New York|Rizzoli]], NYC 2010) collected advice from 1,000 home cooks from around the world who explained what ''not'' to do in the kitchen.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/food/realfood/article1787039.ece/ Alex Renton], ''Never boil and avocado, and other handy tips'', The Times, 20 August 2009</ref><ref name=\"Eat Me Daily\">{{cite web |last1=Forbes |first1=Paula |title=The How Not to Cookbook: Lessons Learned the Hard Way, the Anti-Cookbook \u2013 Eat Me Daily |url=http://www.eatmedaily.com/2009/08/the-how-not-to-cookbook-lessons-learned-the-hard-way-the-anti-cookbook/ |website=Eat Me Daily |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>, ''The How Not to Cookbook: Lessons learned the Hard Way, the Anti-Cookbook'', Eat Me Daily, 24 August 2009</ref>\n\nIn ''First Woman on the Moon'' (1999), Mir converted a Dutch beach into a moonscape for one day with the help of bulldozers.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir1/ Lars Bang Larsen] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203141602/http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir1/ |date=2008-12-03 }}, ''First Woman on the Moon'',  Frieze, London, #50, January 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/life_and_times/ Will Bradley] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110909012739/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/life_and_times/ |date=2011-09-09 }}, ''Life and Times: Aleksandra Mir'', Frieze, Issue 75, 2003</ref><ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all_the_world/ Nancy Spector] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722165740/http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all_the_world/ |date=2011-07-22 }}, ''All the World...'', Frieze, Issue 98, London, April, 2006</ref> The video of this event has been presented at multiple venues,<ref>[http://www.volkskrant.nl/beeldende-kunst/kunstenares-mir-landt-op-strand~a518934/ Jeroen Junte], ''Kunstenares Mir landt op strand'', De Volkskrant, Amsterdam, 27 August 1999</ref><ref>[https://artforum.com/inprint/issue=200302&id=4185// Tim Griffin], ''Openings: Aleksandra Mir'', Artforum, NYC, February 2003</ref> at the [[International Space University]], Strasbourg  <ref>[http://www.isunet.edu/about/master-of-space-studies/faculty-and-lecturers/213 Lecturers], International Space University, Strasbourg, 2015</ref> and at the UK Space Conference, Liverpool, 2015.<ref>[http://ukspace2015.co.uk/speakers Speakers], UK Space Conference, Liverpool, 2015</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Mir painted the [[Mandela Way T-34 Tank]] pink with [[Cubitt Artists]].<ref>{{cite news | last=Gibbs | first=Jonathan | title=Talk of the Town: Pink Tank | date=2 November 2003 | publisher=The Independent on Sunday | url=http://www.aleksandramir.info/texts/gibbs.html | access-date=2017-01-01 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050904183740/http://www.aleksandramir.info/texts/gibbs.html | archive-date=2005-09-04 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFor ''Newsroom 1986\u20132000'' (2007), Mir with a group of assistants copied 240 NYC tabloid covers in felt-tip marker and mounted them in an ever-revolving installation to simulate the daily workings of a Manhattan newsroom.<ref>[http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir2/ Steven Stern] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100828115935/http://www.frieze.com/issue/review/aleksandra_mir2/ |date=2010-08-28 }}, ''Newsroom'', Frieze, #115, London, May 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/yesterdays-front-page-turns-into-todays-art/article1327587/ Simon Houpt], ''Yesterday's front page turns into today's art'', The Globe and Mail, Toronto, October 22, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/20/arts/design/20head.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=aleksandra%20mir&st=cse Roberta Smith], ''New York Stories: Art Torn Screaming From the Headlines, Then Hung on Walls'', New York Times, October 20, 2007</ref><ref>[http://arthistorian.wordpress.com/page/2/ gninja], ''Review of \"Newsroom 1986 \u2013 2000\": What Is Roberta Smith Going on About?'', Art(h)ist'ry, 20 October 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.brooklynrail.org/2007/11/artseen/mir Jen Schwarting], ''Aleksandra Mir Newsroom 1986-2000'', The Brooklyn Rail, NYC, November, 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/09/911-art-empire-150910054837804.html James Reinl], ''9/11 art and the 'Course of Empire' '', Al Jazeera, NYC, 10 September 2015</ref> Mir has created a series of large scale murals using only [[Sharpie (marker)|Sharpie]] marker pens.<ref>[http://diepresse.com/home/kultur/kunst/4736377/Albertina_Zeichnungen-zimmern  Johanna Hofleitner], ''Albertina: Zeichnungen zimmern'', Die Presse, Vienna, 21 May 2015</ref>\n\nIn ''Triumph'' she collected 2529 trophies from the general public of Sicily and exhibited them all in one installation at the Schirn Kunsthalle, Frankfurt (2009). It traveled to the [[South London Gallery]] for the [[London Olympics]] in 2012.<ref>[http://www.itsnicethat.com/articles/aleksandra-mir Catherine Gaffney], ''Going for Gold: Aleksandra Mir investigates our relationship with the trophy'', itsnicethat, London, July, 2012</ref>\n\nMir has created ''Plane Landing'', a real size helium inflatable jet plane, meant not to fly, but to hover above the ground as \"a sculpture of a jet plane in a permanent state of landing\".<ref>[http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/a-sligo-group-show-dreams-big-and-succeeds-visual-art-round-up-1.2332129 Aidan Dunne], ''A Sligo group show dreams big and succeeds'', The Irish Times, Dublin, 10 September 2015</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs]\n\n<ref name=tate>Stuart Comer, Valentina Ravaglia ([s.d.]). [http://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/display/aleksandra-mir Aleksandra Mir]. Tate Modern. Accessed March 2016.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sculpture-unlimited.info/archive/en/aleksandra_mir_en.html Sculpture Unlimited, Institute for the Fine Arts and Cultural Studies, Linz, Austria]\n* [http://oceans.taraexpeditions.org/en/m/art/artists/aleksandra-mir/ Tara Expeditions, Antarctica]\n* [https://drawingroom.org.uk/resources/aleksandra-mir/ Aleksandra Mir at Drawing Room, London]\n* [http://whitney.org/Exhibitions/AmericaIsHardToSee?&artwork_id=7923&filter_id=36/ Aleksandra Mir at Whitney Museum of American Art, New York]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160306014246/http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york/collections/collection-online/artwork/15529/ Aleksandra Mir at Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, New York]\n* [http://www.southlondongallery.org/page/pursuit-of-perfection/ Aleksandra Mir at South London Gallery]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mir, Aleksandra}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The New School alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish women artists]]\n[[Category:B\u00e2loise Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Swedish contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Swedish women artists]]\n", "name_user": "Astwn", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove stray tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aleksandra_Mir"}
